<HL>
   Brady Says Cost
   Of S&amp;L Bailout
   Could Double
   ---
   Bill Could Be $300 Billion,
   Including Interest, and
   Taxpayers Will Foot It
   ----
   By Paulette Thomas
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES
</CO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
</IN>
<GV>
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Bush administration acknowledged that
the cost of the savings and loan cleanup could nearly double,
and said the government borrowing needed to finance it could
produce upward pressure on interest rates.
   Ultimately, Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady told
Congress yesterday, the taxpayer is on the hook for the new
costs.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Previously, the Bush administration estimated that $50
billion would cover the costs of closing down all the S&amp;Ls
that became insolvent through 1992, with another $23 billion
required for thrifts that went under after 1992. The
administration now estimates those costs at between $90
billion and $130 billion.
   Those numbers don't include billions of dollars in
interest on borrowings to finance the cleanup, plus
additional costs of S&amp;L sales in 1988. When those expenses
are added, the cost over 10 years could approach $300
billion, compared with $166 billion that the administration
previously forecast.
   The S&amp;L industry, paying higher deposit-insurance premiums
and other assessments associated with the bailout, can't
provide any of the added cash. "Additional resources will
have to come from Treasury funds," Mr. Brady told the Senate
Banking Committee.
   Mr. Brady played down the importance of the current S&amp;L
costs in President Bush's call for a budget summit with
congressional leaders. When asked why the summit was called
at this time, the secretary replied: "It's budget time."
   But at a separate Senate hearing yesterday, White House
Budget Director Richard Darman said the S&amp;L costs figured
prominently. "The prospect of all this additional borrowing
in a compressed period . . . could lead to upward pressure on
interest rates," threatening economic growth, Mr. Darman
said.
   "Higher interest rates could mean the economy goes from
growth -- although it's too slow growth -- into recession,"
Mr. Darman told a Senate appropriations subcommittee. "It's
important we have a deficit-reduction package to avoid upward
pressure on interest rates." Because the government can't
avoid borrowing to finance the S&amp;L cleanup, he argued, it
should reduce borrowing for other purposes.
   Congress has been skeptical of the cost estimates of the
bailout since the plan was announced in February 1989. The
General Accounting Office, the investigative arm of Congress,
estimated last month that the total cleanup costs would reach
$140 billion, not including interest.
   The original Bush plan assumed there would be no
inflation, that thrift deposits would grow steadily, and that
fewer new S&amp;Ls would fail. Instead, interest rates have risen
about one percentage point, the real estate market -- the
investment vehicle for most S&amp;Ls -- is weak, more thrifts
have become insolvent than expected, and buyers for insolvent
thrifts have been scarce.
   "This is an unmitigated disaster," said Rep. Thomas
McMillen (D., Md.). "I think we are going to continue to see
these numbers racheted upward."
   The Resolution Trust Corp., the agency that sells
insolvent thrifts, already has 423 thrifts under its control,
and in new estimates announced yesterday, the Office of
Thrift Supervision said that it projects another 299
failures. Beyond that, 315 other S&amp;Ls are considered possible
failures, depending on economic conditions. If many more in
the borderline group fail, it would push the costs toward the
high end of the administration estimates.
   The final costs won't be known until the investments of
the government-seized thrifts are sold to the private sector.
In the thrift assets sold so far, losses have ranged from 14%
to 23% of book value, a senior administration official said.
That doesn't include losses that the government acquired when
it took over the thrifts.
   Despite slow sales of the thrift assets and added costs,
Congress should resist the temptation to tinker with the new
S&amp;L law -- with the exception of appropriating new funds, Mr.
Brady said. He advised Congress to provide indefinite
authority to fund the rest of the cleanup, rather than in
increments.
   ---
   David Wessel contributed to this article.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900524-0073
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900524-0073.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media -- Advertising:
   Seagram Acts to Renew Wine-Cooler Fizz
   ----
   By Thomas R. King
</HL>
<DATE>
05/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST VO CDGB AFP EUROP AEGSY F.EUC WNEWS WPPGY IPG
</CO>
<IN>
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
BEVERAGES (BVG)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Those fizzy, fruity wine coolers are dead as a doornail,
gone the way of the mood ring into fad heaven. Or are they?
   Seagram Co., in an unusual bid to regain the confidence of
retailers, is running multipage ads in Beverage Dynamics and
other trade magazines claiming, "Reports on the death of
coolers have been greatly exaggerated." The ad lists "cooler
facts and fiction" and pleads with retailers to support the
brand with display and shelf space.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Seagram pitch comes as total sales of wine coolers
continue in a downward spiral. Last year, sales dropped 19.4%
to 39.5 million cases, according to Jobson Publishing Co.'s
beverage alcohol group. The drop followed an 11% drop the
year before.
   But Seagram is ignoring the precipitous slide of the past
few years and looking at the brighter side: For the past six
months, category sales are actually flat, it says, adding
that sales of Seagram coolers are up recently.
   "We wanted to get the facts as they exist in today's
marketplace clearly across to the public that distributes and
sells these products to consumers," says Mark Taxel,
executive vice president at Seagram Beverage Co. "The
category decline was coming from a lot of the second-tier
brands that never gave the consumer quality."
   Some Seagram competitors take exception. "The wine-cooler
category just really disappeared," says a spokeswoman for
Philip Morris's Miller Brewing unit, which pulled the plug on
its Matilda Bay cooler brand late last year. "The category
started to disintegrate, and it wasn't an economically
feasible thing to stay in."
   Actually, both sides may be right. The cooler category did
indeed shrink drastically since the summer of 1987 -- but the
exodus of numerous wine-cooler makers like Miller has been
good news for Seagram and E&amp;J Gallo Winery, which makes
Bartles &amp; Jaymes. Both heavyweights have picked up share, and
together they now account for about 80% of total sales.
   "Certainly there was a fad aspect to wine coolers," says
Jon Fredrikson, a wine-industry economist at Gomberg,
Fredrikson &amp; Associates, San Francisco. "But there was a
major shakeout," he says, and the survivors have carved a
healthy business.
   Seagram isn't taking any chances. In addition to the pitch
aimed at retailers, it hired a new ad agency, Wells, Rich,
Greene, and this week wheels out a new ad campaign in
anticipation of summer, when the majority of coolers are
consumed.
   The new campaign, themed "it's a cooler world," has a
decidedly middlebrow feel to it, with men and women shown
sitting around a table exchanging lively conversation. "We
talked about guys, we talked about girls, hey that's what
life's all about anyway," goes part of a jingle sung by
Nikolas Ashford and Valerie Simpson.
   Indeed, the ads don't even attempt to woo the
trend-setting poolside types that sampled coolers but didn't
stick with the product. The target customers "aren't trendy
people," Mr. Taxel says. "Our consumers tend to be a little
more upscale than regular beer drinkers."
   For its new effort, Seagram has abandoned its all-star
strategy.
   After using Bruce Willis for a time, the company in 1988
brought out three other celebrities, including Woody
Harrelson, Steve Guttenberg and Anne Archer.
   The new campaign will promote in particular Seagram's new
Black Raspberry wine cooler. When the category started to
falter, most wine-cooler makers resorted to aggressive
introductions of new flavors to hold consumer interest, but
the innovations didn't help stem the declines.
   Canandaigua Wine Co.'s Sun Country cooler, for example,
brought out several flavored coolers, but its share
plummeted. It's now a minor player, but it's planning another
run and is introducing yet another flavor, Melon Berry. But
it doesn't plan to allocate any money to national TV
advertising, instead planning to sponsor special events in a
few markets where the brand continues to sell.
   For its part, Gallo says it plans to stick with Frank
Bartles and Ed Jaymes, its two folksy pitchmen, for TV
commercials. A spokesman says Bartles &amp; Jaymes, like Seagram,
had a strong first quarter. "We don't see anything wrong with
the business."
   ---
   Art, Glasnost and Vodka
                                                                                                       

   Glasnost has already been used to sell everything from
McDonald's to Quintessence cosmetics. Now vodkas are trading
on it in a bid for Russian cachet.
   Absolut Vodka said yesterday it will run ads highlighting
works by 26 Russian artists in the June Interview magazine.
The paintings and sculptures featured have, not surprisingly,
one thing in common: Each includes a bottle of Absolut, which
sounds Russian but is actually a Swedish spirit imported by
Carillon Importers Ltd. in New York. TBWA Advertising created
the ads.
   The Absolut ads follow a new campaign for Smirnoff vodka,
which recently was reintroduced in the Soviet Union after 73
years. The headline: "Back in the USSR." Smirnoff has been
produced in the U.S. by Heublein Inc. for 50 years.
   ---
