<HL>
   Marketing &amp; Media:
   Turner to Launch Version
   Of TNT for Latin America
</HL>
<DATE>
05/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   TBSA LATAM
</CO>
<IN>
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   ATLANTA -- Turner Broadcasting System Inc. said it plans
to launch in January a Latin American and Caribbean version
of its Turner Network Television entertainment station.
   The planned network, code-named "TNT South" by Turner
executives, is part of the growing globalization of U.S.
cable networks. Turner's Cable News Network already reaches
viewers all over the world; and other cable channels,
including MTV and ESPN, are distributed in Europe and Japan.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Scott Sassa, TNT's executive vice president, said the new
channel will include TNT's regular fare of old movies,
theatrical cartoons and documentaries, subtitled in Spanish.
Eventually, he said Turner hopes to beam multiple sound and
subtitle tracks with its video images, so that viewers will
be able to see TNT in English, Spanish or Portuguese.
   Mr. Sassa said TNT South will consist of a single
eight-hour block of programming, which will be repeated with
slight variations, three times a day. The satellite feed will
be downloaded by cable operators, direct-broadcast satellite
services and hotels, who will distribute it to viewers. Mr.
Sassa said TNT South is costing Turner "considerably less" to
launch than the $30 million it spent on TNT, but he wouldn't
elaborate. He said Turner expects to break even on TNT South
in three to five years.
   "We view this as the first step toward establishing a
world-wide entertainment network," Mr. Sassa added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900524-0060
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900524-0060.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Novell Inc.'s Results
   For Fiscal-2nd Period
   Surpass Expectations
</HL>
<DATE>
05/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   NOVL
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   PROVO, Utah -- Novell Inc. reported
higher-than-anticipated results for the fiscal-second
quarter, reflecting the continuing boom in the business of
tying computers together in networks.
   For the quarter ended April 28, Novell said profit rose
78% to $20.5 million, or 60 cents a share, from $11.5
million, or 35 cents share, a year ago. Revenue rose 9% to
$120 million from $110.4 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Most analysts expected earnings of 53 to 54 cents a share
and revenue in the range of $114 million to $118 million.
   Novell principally provides software that allows personal
computers to share printers, information and programs. The
company said the latest quarter's results reflect the
profitable effect of having a growing share of its revenue --
75% compared with 63% a year earlier -- come from software
sales. "There is a direct correlation between that and our
gross margins," a spokesman said.
   Novell said the results reflected $400,000 in expenses
from its recently aborted merger with Lotus Development
Corp., Cambridge, Mass. The $1.5 billion transaction fell
through last weekend after the two companies couldn't agree
on the composition of a combined board. Novell said
"additional immaterial merger costs" would be recognized in
the fiscal-third quarter.
   For the six months, Novell said profit rose 58% to $35.6
million, or $1.05 a share, on revenue of $225.9 million, from
profit of $22.5 million, or 68 cents a share, on revenue of
$209.1 million a year earlier.
   The results were announced after markets had closed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
