<HL>
   Abreast of the Market:
   Industrials Inch Up to New High
   Despite Pressure of Profit-Taking
   ----
   By David Wilson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The Dow Jones Industrial Average kept this
week's string of all-time highs intact, as late buying pushed
the stock market higher in moderately active trading.
   Although profit-taking in response to the market's
record-breaking rally put share prices under pressure for
most of the session, the industrial average eked out a gain
of 4.03 to 2856.26.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The average managed to set its third consecutive record
close -- and the sixth in the past eight sessions -- despite
heavy selling in Westinghouse Electric and weakness in a
number of blue-chip oil stocks, reflecting a sharp decline in
oil prices.
   "The market is still exhibiting a decided reluctance to
give in to profit-taking," said Eugene E. Peroni Jr.,
director of technical research at Janney Montgomery Scott,
Philadelphia.
   Standard &amp; Poor's 500-Stock Index rose 0.86 to 359.29,
about half a point from its all-time high of 359.80, set last
Oct. 9. The Dow Jones Equity Market Index went up 0.68 to
334.28 and the New York Stock Exchange Composite Index gained
0.27 to 195.85.
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by 761 to 745 on
the Big Board, where volume fell to 172,330,000 shares from
203,350,000 Tuesday.
   Stocks got off to a slow start as market players reacted
negatively to early weakness in bonds, which dropped in spite
of news that April orders for durable goods fell 4.1% -- a
sharper decline than expected.
   After sliding to session lows at midday, the market
briefly turned mixed at midafternoon on some
arbitrage-related buy programs, in which traders sold
stock-index futures contracts and bought baskets of stocks in
order to lock in profits from price differences between them.
   But when the bond market rebound that preceded the move in
stocks faded, share prices did the same, and they didn't turn
higher until the final minutes of trading.
   Some additional arbitrage-related buying and short
covering contributed to the upturn, said John Burnett, a
senior vice president of block trading at Donaldson, Lufkin &amp;
Jenrette, but he added that "real, no-kidding-around buying"
from institutions also surfaced.
   "We saw good solid buying across the board," Mr. Burnett
said, adding that portfolio managers are "afraid of missing
the boat" if the market should continue its advance instead
of giving them a chance to purchase stocks at lower prices.
   "Any kind of pullbacks here are going to be very nominal,
and I think you're going to see a lot of money flooding into
the market" on any weakness, added Alexander M. Purdie Jr.,
head of block trading at Robinson-Humphrey Co., Atlanta. "The
market's still looking very attractive in a lot of ways."
   Westinghouse fell 1 1/4 to 34 3/4 in Big Board composite
trading of 1.9 million shares. Shearson Lehman Hutton reduced
its investment ratings on the stock, citing expectations of a
slowdown in its earnings growth next year, and lowered its
1990 and 1991 earnings estimates.
   Oil stocks among the Dow industrials to show weakness
included Exxon, which went down 1/2 to 47 3/8; Texaco, down
1/2 to 59 3/8, and Chevron, off 5/8 to 69 3/8. But USX gained
3/4 to 33 3/4 and Du Pont, which owns Conoco, rose 1/2 to 40
3/8.
   July crude-oil futures tumbled 78 cents a barrel to $18.14
in New York trading, and the plunge left its mark on other
major oil stocks. Amoco fell 1/2 to 53 1/4, Mobil slipped 1/4
to 62 1/8 and Unocal slid 1/2 to 30 3/4.
   Several airline stocks dropped despite the oil market's
weakness, which could lead to lower fuel costs, after Trans
World Airlines announced that it would lower domestic
round-trip fares by as much as 30%. AMR, which owns American
Airlines, fell 1/2 to 64 1/2; Delta Air Lines lost 1 to 76
1/2, and USAir Group lost 1 3/8 to 27 7/8.
   Deere tumbled 2 7/8 to 73 on 1.7 million shares as a
second day of profit-taking weighed down the stock, which set
a 52-week high during Tuesday's session but posted a decline
of 1 5/8 points. Wertheim Schroder removed the stock from a
list of recommended issues and lowered its investment rating,
citing its belief that Deere's shares were fully valued.
   Compaq Computer, a star performer in the market's climb to
record highs, added 3 1/2 to 122 7/8. Moody's Investors
Service upgraded its rating on a $200 million debt issue that
Compaq has called for redemption; the agency cited the
company's cash flow and strong balance sheet as reasons for
its action.
   Other technology issues also added to their recent gains,
including Texas Instruments, which gained 2 1/8 to 43 3/8 as
1.3 million shares changed hands. International Business
Machines advanced 1 to 118 3/4, Digital Equipment gained 1
3/4 to 93 1/4 and Hewlett-Packard rose 1 1/8 to 47 3/8. But
Unisys, left behind in the sector's rally, slipped 1/8 to 14
1/8.
   On the other hand, precious-metals stocks paced the
market's retreat amid a sharp decline in the price of gold.
Homestake Mining dropped 1 3/8 to 18 3/8, Placer Dome dipped
1 to 16 1/8, Battle Mountain Gold lost 5/8 to 13 1/4 and ASA
Ltd. retreated 2 3/8 to 49 1/8 in Big Board dealings. On the
American Stock Exchange, Echo Bay Mines fell 1/2 to 13,
Pegasus Gold lost 3/4 to 11 1/4 and Corona A dropped 1/2 to 7
1/8.
   Citicorp fell 7/8 to 22 7/8 in the aftermath of Moody's
downgrading of credit ratings on the bank holding company and
its Citibank unit. The move included Citicorp's commercial
paper, which hadn't been affected last month when Standard &amp;
Poor's made a similar move.
   Meanwhile, shares of two other big city banks --
BankAmerica, which gained 3/4 to 30 1/8, and Bankers Trust
New York, which added 1 5/8 to 43 1/2 -- rallied after County
NatWest Securities cited the stocks as better values than
Citicorp. Analyst Stephen Berman said the two companies have
good balance sheets and reasonably good loan quality.
   Ranking high on the Big Board's mostactive list was
Alliance Global Environmental Fund, a new issue, which closed
well above the price of its initial offering. Six million
shares of the closed-end mutual fund were sold at $15 apiece;
the stock rose 6.7% to 16 on trading of 2.1 million shares.
   Thai Capital Fund, the latest entry among single-country
mutual funds, also fared well on its initial day of trading.
The stock closed at 12 3/8, above its initial offering price
of $12 a share.
   British Gas fell 3/4 to 36 after a possible rival bidder
surfaced for Consumers' Gas, which the company has agreed to
acquire.
   ProNational Gas, a firm headed by a former chief financial
officer of Consumers' Gas, said it opposes the proposed
acquisition and plans its own offer.
   Circuit City Stores fell 1 5/8 to 24 7/8. Securities and
Exchange Commission filings show that the company's chairman
and president sold significant portions of their stakes in
Circuit City last month.
   Donaldson, which reported that net income for the fiscal
quarter ended in April rose 61% from a year earlier and
increased its quarterly dividend by about 16%, jumped 2 3/4
to 30.
   The Amex Market Value Index, hurt by the weakness in oil
and gold stocks, fell 0.20 to 359.65. Volume totaled
16,550,000 shares.
   Forest Laboratories rose 1 5/8 to 44. Wertheim Schroder
repeated a buy recommendation on the stock and set price
targets of $55 to $57 a share for the next 12 months and $70
for the next 24 months.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900524-0036
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900524-0036.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Technology:
   Telecommunications Firms
   Attract Venture Capital
</HL>
<DATE>
05/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<IN>
TELEPHONE SYSTEMS (TLS)
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
SOFTWARE (SOF)
SEMICONDUCTORS, INTEGRATED CHIPS (SEM)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Telecommunications companies attracted the
most computer-technology venture capital investment in 1989
while funding of computer software and services companies
fell sharply, according to a survey by Technologic Partners.
   Of the $1.24 billion invested, more than 25%, or $320
million, went to telecommunications products and services
companies. That's an increase of 55%, said Technologic
Partners, a Manhattan-based research firm. It found that
1988's No. 1 target for investment, computer software and
services, fell 23% to $208 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "In the last five years some of the most successful new
companies have been telecommunications companies," said
Richard A. Shaffer, principal at Technologic. Meanwhile, he
said, the computer business has become a hodgepodge of
technologies and players that confounds investors.
   "Seed," or early stage financing, a growing segment in the
past five years, was another loser in 1989, falling 10% to
$62 million, or 33 seed financings, compared with $69
million, or 41 seeds, in 1988.
   While later-stage, or "mezzanine," financings also
declined, middle-stage investments garnered greater support
from investors who held back until companies were well under
way. Mr. Shaffer said this should continue as long as the
market for initial public offerings remains slow.
   Other top targets for investment, according to
Technologic, included computer peripheral companies,
third-ranked at $140 million; integrated circuit
manufacturers ($133 million); and computer systems suppliers
($130 million).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900524-0035
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900524-0035.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Wednesday's Markets:
   Stocks Rise
   On Gains
   In Bonds
   ---
   Shares Down Most
   Of Day; Dollar Is Up
   Against Yen, Mark
   ----
   By Christopher Winans
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Stock prices, which were down most of the day,
eked out a last-minute gain in reaction to the volatile bond
market's midafternoon advances.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average rose 4.03 points to close
at 2856.26, its third consecutive record high, in active
trading. Long-term U.S. Treasury bond prices finished
modestly higher -- up 3/8 point, or $3.75 for each $1,000 of
face amount -- in heavy trading. The dollar gained against
the mark and the yen.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Helping push bond prices higher against periodic waves of
profit-taking were lower commodity prices, particularly gold,
and an economic report that confirmed the economy is slowing.
Durable goods orders in April fell a bit more than had been
expected. This news reinforced views that inflation isn't
getting out of hand. Inflation reduces bonds' investment
appeal.
   Heavy buying by foreign investors also fueled the
bond-market rally, as did comments in Washington that
government borrowing to fund the thrift bailout shouldn't
affect interest rates. Finally, some traders speculated that
some of the money Saudi Arabia raised by selling gold in
London may have found its way into U.S. Treasury securities.
   The stock market tracked bonds much of the day. Along with
the industrial average, Standard &amp; Poor's 500-stock index and
the New York Stock Exchange Composite Index posted their
first gains of the day in the last half hour of trading.
   "Bonds definitely took stocks higher at the last minute,"
said Susan Del Signore, trading vice president at Hartford,
Conn.-based Travelers Investment Management.
   Paul Hennessey, vice president of equities trading at
Boston Co., said the stock market is holding up well and may
inch higher in the next few days. "There's so much money
still on the sidelines looking for an opportunity to get into
the market," he said. But looking further down the road -- a
week to 10 days -- Mr. Hennessey expects a drop of about 100
points.
   After that, he suggests, investors and analysts will look
for fresh signals of the market's next move. For one thing,
he says, "we'll begin to look at where we are in terms of
corporate profits at the end of the second quarter."
   Wayne Wong, managing director in charge of fixed-income
investing at Marinvest, foresees a 200-point correction in
the industrial average just around the corner. He thinks bond
prices will tread water until a clearer picture of the
economy emerges.
   In major market action:
                                                                                                       

   Stock prices rose in active trading, with 172.3 million
shares changing hands on the New York Stock Exchange.
Advancing issues barely outnumbered decliners, 761 to 745.
                                                                                                       

   Bond prices climbed. The yield on the Treasury's benchmark
30-year bond eased to 8.57%.
                                                                                                       

   The dollar gained slightly. In late New York trading, the
currency was quoted at 1.6765 marks and 151.45 yen, compared
with 1.6736 marks and 151.20 yen Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
