<HL>
   TWA Machinists Offer to Take Over
   Airline; Icahn Would Keep Other Assets
   ----
   By Judith Valente
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   TWA LABOR X AWAL
</CO>
<IN>
AIRLINES (AIR)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   Trans World Airlines Inc.'s machinists union offered owner
Carl C. Icahn a framework under which employees would take
control of the ailing carrier.
   The union said it proposed acquiring 100% of TWA through
an employee stock ownership plan that would also include the
carrier's pilots, flight attendants and nonunion employees.
The labor group hasn't yet made a formal offer, saying it
hasn't completed an evaluation of TWA's assets.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   However, the union is expected to argue that the carrier
currently has a negative value that removes the necessity for
employees to pay anything for it. Under the machinists' plan,
employees would take over only the airline. Mr. Icahn would
keep TWA's investments in such other companies as USX Corp.
Those investments are valued at between $1 billion and $1.6
billion. The union also wants Mr. Icahn to remain responsible
for the company's debt.
   Mr. Icahn has been seeking to unload the unprofitable
carrier for months. Such a plan would allow him to "exit
gracefully," said machinist union leader Timothy Connolly.
   If the machinists' proposal progresses, TWA would become
the second major carrier where employees are seeking to take
control. Last month, UAL Corp.'s board approved a $4.38
billion buy-out proposal from United Airlines unions. The UAL
unions have until Aug. 9 to finance their offer.
   The TWA machinists took their inspiration for the plan
from a threat Mr. Icahn made a few weeks ago to transfer
TWA's domestic route system to America West Airlines Inc. But
a transfer of assets won't prove easy.
   TWA is $2.8 billion in debt, the result of a 1988
transaction in which Mr. Icahn took the carrier private. The
employee group doesn't want to assume responsibility for the
debt. But it is unlikely Mr. Icahn would agree to remain
responsible for it.
   Mr. Icahn said he is open to an employee takeover, but
called the machinists' proposal "a pretty tough deal." He
said before talks can proceed, he wants assurances that the
employees would make concessions to keep the airline going.
He also said he is concerned about labor's ability to
continue making lease payments on aircraft an
Icahn-controlled company owns.
   TWA, which had losses of $298 million last year, has been
staggering under the weight of about $490 million in annual
debt service. It has already posted losses of $143 million in
the first three months of this year, when higher costs for
fuel, service and maintenance were factors.
   Employee owners would inherit the fundamental problem that
has plagued TWA for years. It is largely an international
carrier with a small domestic route system to feed its
overseas flights. It faces increased competition from foreign
carriers and U.S. carriers with vast domestic routes.
   The machinists union contends that the employees, as
owners, would be willing to provide wage concessions and
productivity gains needed to fund growth at the airline.
TWA's unions have refused Mr. Icahn any further concessions.
In turn, Mr. Icahn has postponed placing additional orders
for new aircraft and resisted making other capital
investments in TWA.
   The machinists' proposal needs the support of other TWA
unions to succeed. Leaders of the pilots and flight
attendants unions said they would support a change in
ownership, but aren't certain the machinists' proposal can
succeed.
   Whether or not the proposal succeeds, TWA's debt needs to
be restructured in order for the airline to survive, said
pilots union leader William Compton. Mr. Compton said the
pilots are also looking into an arrangement whereby TWA
creditors would exchange debt they hold for common stock in
the airline.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900524-0006
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900524-0006.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   India Gives
   Final Approval
   To Pepsi's Plans
   ---
   Firm's Joint Venture There
   To Spend Over $1 Billion
   During the Next Decade
   ----
   By Michael J. McCarthy
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6
</SO>
<CO>
   PEP MDEST
</CO>
<IN>
BEVERAGES (BVG)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   PepsiCo Inc. said it has received final approval from the
government of India to sell soft drinks and said its joint
venture there plans to spend more than $1 billion to build
Pepsi's food and beverage businesses over the next decade.
   Although the full joint venture was approved by the Indian
government in 1988, Pepsi said opposition from India's
soft-drink industry created considerable uncertainty in the
past two months that Pepsi would receive final clearance to
sell soft drinks.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As an almost undeveloped market, India represents vast
potential for Pepsi. In a country of some 800 million people,
Indians annually drink only about 80 million cases of soda --
the same amount sold in Seattle. On a per-capita basis,
Indians drink about three bottles of soft drinks a year,
compared with more than 700 in the U.S.
   "This market could literally quadruple on a per-capita
basis over 10 years," said Chistopher A. Sinclair, president
of PepsiCola International. Pepsi is pinning its hopes on
India's growing middle class, currently estimated to comprise
some 150 million people. By year-end, Pepsi plans to
distribute its products in Calcutta, Bombay, Punjab and
Delhi, among other places.
   "We're not expecting to make money right away," said Mr.
Sinclair. "We'll be investing the cash flow in the business
for a long time." However, Pepsi, based in Purchase, N.Y.,
does expect to be making a profit in India within five or six
years, he said.
   Coupled with Pepsi's recent 10-year agreement to sell soft
drinks in the Soviet Union, the Indian business gives Pepsi
another boost in its campaign to compete globally with rival
Coca-Cola Co.
   Coke, which outsells Pepsi more than 2-to-1
internationally, withdrew from India in 1977 over a dispute
with the government that would have required disclosure of
Coke's secret formula. In March, the government denied Coke's
request to re-enter India. Unable to make money after four
years in the mid-1950s, Pepsi itself abandoned the India
market.
   One cloud looms over Pepsi's otherwise bright Indian
summer. Last year, the U.S. called India an unfair trading
partner under the so-called Super 301 provision of the 1988
U.S. trade law, alleging that India's strict regulations
hindered foreign investment. The Super 301 provision requires
retaliation if countries don't resolve trade practices the
U.S. deems unfair.
   Pepsi wouldn't speculate about what might happen to its
Indian venture as a result of any retaliatory flare-up, but
it isn't taking chances, either. The company recently sent a
letter to U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills, stating that
it thinks the Indian approval of the Pepsi venture signals a
laudable openness to foreign investment. "We hope that our
government will not have to take any actions {against India}
under the Super 301 process," the letter added.
   Through negotiations that began six years ago, Pepsi was
able to crack the Indian market in 1988, by winning over the
government with a package of political sweeteners, including
food-processing plants.
   Pepsi's India joint venture -- consisting of Pepsi, a
private Indian conglomerate, and a government agricultural
agency -- also makes snack-food products. The venture
partners, along with Indian franchisees, will make the $1
billion investment. Over the next decade, Pepsi estimates
that the retail sales of its snacks and soft drinks in India
will total $2.5 billion.
   Now Pepsi has new hurdles. For one thing, it will have to
compete with Parle Beverages Ltd., India's biggest soft-drink
company. Led by flagship Thumbs Up cola, Parle holds an
estimated 60% of the $500 million soft-drink market. And,
given the structure of Indian retailing, there are few big
stores for Pepsi to try to win over to make an immediate
splash. Sales battles will likely be protracted
mini-skirmishes over thousands of mom-and-pop outlets, where
shoppers buy one bottle at a time.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900524-0005
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900524-0005.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   OTC Focus:
   Market Jumps Past Big Board Gains;
   Technologies Remain the Driving Force
   ----
   By Anne Newman
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/24/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C6
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   Over-the-counter stocks sprinted past the Dow Jones
Industrial Average as technology shares again led the OTC
market.
   The Nasdaq Composite Index rose 2.98 to 456.87, a 0.66%
gain compared with the 0.14% rise in the Dow industrials.
However, while the Dow average set another record, the Nasdaq
index remains almost 30 points below its high of 485.73 set
last Oct. 9.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Nasdaq 100 index, which tracks larger industrial
issues including technology stocks, jumped 6.43 to 472.12, a
1.38% advance. Advancing shares overtook decliners late in
the day, 1,086 to 947. Stocks hitting new highs again
outpaced new lows, 188 to 71. Volume remained hefty at 188.7
million, down from 190.1 million Tuesday.
   "From a trader's standpoint, the OTC market looks really
healthy," said Ralph Costanza, managing director of OTC
trading at Smith Barney, Harris Upham. Mr. Costanza explained
that technology shares are providing the leadership needed to
pull smaller stocks higher. Big computer stocks, he
explained, attract both large institutions and smaller
investors.
   Mr. Costanza also said he was heartened by the orderly
demand for OTC shares. "Once they start throwing caution to
the wind and start buying anything, then we have to worry,"
he said. "But I'm not seeing that kind of rampant
speculation."
   Investors trading through A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons in St. Louis
bought a broad spectrum of stocks, according to Robert
McCready, an OTC trader there. "We saw them pecking away at
some of the banks that have been under pressure," Mr.
McCready said.
   Intel traded to a new 52-week high after Merrill Lynch
picked the issue as its "Focus Stock of the Week," according
to Dow Jones Professional Investor Report. Shares of the
Santa Clara, Calif., semiconductor maker rose 2 to 48; Intel
was the day's second most active issue.
   Microsoft jumped 4 3/8 to 75 7/8 on 1.9 million shares
after Wednesday's much-heralded unveiling of the Redmond,
Wash., software maker's Windows 3.0 package.
   Oracle Systems was the most active issue, gaining 1 to 19
3/4 on 3.1 million shares. Tuesday, the Belmont, Calif.,
database management software maker created a separate
operating subsidiary and reorganized its management.
   Goal Systems jumped 2 1/8 to 17 1/8 after the Columbus,
Ohio, maker of IBM-compatible software announced a loss for
the first quarter ended April 30 of 12 cents a share,
compared with restated net income a year earlier of six
cents. However, that loss included a charge of 20 cents
related to one-time merger and acquisition expenses.
   Culp added 1/4 to 8 1/4 after the High Point, N.C.,
textile company said it expects to report a profit for the
fourth quarter ended April 29 and a net gain for the year,
compared with a loss of 20 cents a share in fiscal 1989.
   Long Lake Energy added 1/4 to 2 3/4. The New York
developer of electric power plants said it finalized a line
of credit agreement with its principal shareholders and that
its outside auditors removed an April 3 statement expressing
concern about Long Lake's ability to continue as an ongoing
business.
   Biotechnology stocks continued to bubble as analysts
highlighted them. Chiron rose 2 1/2 to 32 1/2 after
Oppenheimer analyst Jeffrey Casdin added the stock to the
brokerage firm's list of issues recommended for purchase,
according to DJPIR. According to another person at
Oppenheimer, Mr. Casdin cited prospects for the Emeryville,
Calif., company's hepatitis C test.
   Prudential-Bache biotechnology analyst Stuart Weisbrod
recommended investors sell shares of Centocor and Genzyme and
buy Immunex, Cetus and Amgen, DJPIR reported. Genzyme eased
3/8 to 19 3/8; Centocor, down earlier in the day, gained 1/2
to 41 1/2. Amgen rose 2 3/4 to 74.
   Shares of Immunex, which Tuesday received a favorable
review of its drug to stimulate white-blood-cell production,
climbed 2 1/4 to 21 3/4.
   Cetus advanced 5/8 to 17 1/8. In addition to Mr.
Weisbrod's comments, Cetus traded higher in the wake of
Wednesday's announcement that the Emeryville, Calif., company
won a round in a patent dispute with Erbamont Inc. over a
widely prescribed anti-tumor drug that it imports. More than
1.4 million shares changed hands, nearly six times average
volume.
   The day's most prominent loser was Intermec, which plunged
4 1/2 to 18 1/4 on 2.2 million shares. Late Tuesday, the
Lynnwood, Wash., maker of electronic bar-code printers,
scanners and related products, reported net income for the
fourth quarter ended March 31 of 43 cents a share, flat with
a year earlier.
   American Republic Bancorp slid 1/2 to 7 1/4 after its
president and chief executive officer, John B. O'Donnell,
resigned. The Torrance, Calif., bank said only that Mr.
O'Donnell resigned because "he may have inadvertently engaged
in activities which appear inconsistent with company policy,"
but didn't provide further details.
   Agnico-Eagle Mines lost 1 to 7 1/8, giving back Tuesday's
5/8 gain. The Canadian gold mining company said it plans to
proceed with a planned offering of 40 million Canadian
dollars (US$34 million) of shares and warrants that was
challenged by a shareholder, Jacque Forget. Tuesday, Mr.
Forget said he plans to establish a group of investors to
pursue a takeover bid for the company. Yesterday,
Agnico-Eagle also called Mr. Forget's comments about alleged
management errors "completely unfounded."
   Possis extended its losses. Tuesday, the Minneapolis
contract engineering and computer-aided design concern
reported net income for the third quarter ended April 30 of
one cent a share, compared with a year-earlier loss of 10
cents. The stock fell 1/8 to 4 1/8 after Tuesday's 1/8-point
drop.
   ---
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications
                                                                                                       

   CENTOCOR Inc. and Genzyme Corp. shares were downgraded to
"hold" from "buy" by Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
biotechnology analyst Stuart Weisbrod. Yesterday's OTC Focus
column said Mr. Weisbrod advised investors to sell those two
stocks and buy others he is recommending, but
Prudential-Bache said such action was suggested only for
"aggressive accounts." Mr. Weisbrod wasn't available for
comment, but Prudential-Bache made a copy of his research
report available.
   (WSJ May 25, 1990)
</TEXT>
